## NASA Goddard Space Flight Center, Space Weather Research Center ( SWRC )
## Message Type: Weekly Space Weather Summary Report for June 19, 2019 - June 25, 2019
##
## Message Issue Date: 2019-06-26T21:54:30Z
## Report Coverage Begin Date: 2019-06-19T00:00Z
## Report Coverage End Date: 2019-06-25T23:59Z
## Message ID: 20190626-7D-001
##
## Disclaimer: NOAA's Space Weather Prediction Center (http://swpc.noaa.gov) is the United States Government official source for space weather forecasts. This "Experimental Research Information" consists of preliminary NASA research products and should be interpreted and used accordingly.


## Summary:

Solar activity was at low levels during this reporting period. There were no significant flares or CMEs.  

Geomagnetic activity was at below minor levels with Kp index (a measure of geomagnetic activity, ranging 0-9) <=3 for the reporting period. 

The > 0.8 MeV energetic electron flux detected at GOES remained below the threshold level of 10^5 pfu for the entire reporting period. 

The energetic proton flux of >10 MeV protons detected at GOES and the 13-100 MeV protons at STEREO A were all at background levels for the entire reporting period. 

Space Weather Impact:
Space weather impacts on NASA spacecraft are expected to have been low this week.

Flares (M-class and above)

None Observed

None Observed 

Non-Earth directed:
Starting time        Speed (km/s)   Type   Direction (LON/LAT in HEEQ)   Half-Angle width (degrees)  Detecting spacecraft (real-time)

## Space Weather Outlook:
## Outlook Coverage Begin Date: 2019-06-26T00:00Z 
## Outlook Coverage End Date:  2019-07-02T23:59Z

Solar activity is expected to be low for the upcoming week.  Geomagnetic activity is expected to be low to moderate for the upcoming week due to the arrival of a high speed stream from a diffuse coronal hole around 2019-06-26.

## NASA Goddard Space Flight Center, Space Weather Research Center ( SWRC )
## Message Type: Weekly Space Weather Summary Report for June 12, 2019 - June 18, 2019
##
## Message Issue Date: 2019-06-19T21:51:54Z
## Report Coverage Begin Date: 2019-06-12T00:00Z
## Report Coverage End Date: 2019-06-18T23:59Z
## Message ID: 20190619-7D-001
##
## Disclaimer: NOAA's Space Weather Prediction Center (http://swpc.noaa.gov) is the United States Government official source for space weather forecasts. This "Experimental Research Information" consists of preliminary NASA research products and should be interpreted and used accordingly.


## Summary:

Solar activity was at low levels during this reporting period.  There was 1 C-type CME (see details below).   

Geomagnetic activity was at below minor levels with Kp index (a measure of geomagnetic activity, ranging 0-9) <=4 for the reporting period.  The highest value of Kp=4 occurred during the synoptic period of 2019-06-13T21:00Z-24:00Z.  This slight elevation of geomagnetic activity was associated with the arrival of a weak coronal hole high speed stream detected by DSCOVR and ACE at L1 around 2019-06-12.  The solar wind speed reached values of ~495 km/s 2019-06-13.  

The STEREO-A/IMPACT and PLASTIC instruments detected the arrival of a coronal hole high speed stream around 2019-06-12.  The solar wind speed reached values of ~550 km/s around 2019-06-13.  

The > 0.8 MeV energetic electron flux detected at GOES remained below the threshold level of 10^5 pfu for the entire reporting period. 

The energetic proton flux of >10 MeV protons detected at GOES and the 13-100 MeV protons at STEREO A were all at background levels for the entire reporting period. 

Space Weather Impact:
Space weather impacts on NASA spacecraft are expected to have been low this week.

Flares (M-class and above)
None Observed

Earth directed:
None Observed

## Space Weather Outlook:

## Outlook Coverage End Date:  2019-06-25T23:59Z

The solar activity is expected to be low for the next reporting period.  Geomagnetic activity is expected to be low to moderate for the upcoming week due to the possible arrival of a weak coronal hole high speed stream around 2019-06-20.

## NASA Goddard Space Flight Center, Space Weather Research Center ( SWRC )
## Message Type: Weekly Space Weather Summary Report for May 29, 2019 - June 04, 2019
##
## Message Issue Date: 2019-06-06T16:24:38Z
## Report Coverage Begin Date: 2019-05-29T00:00Z
## Report Coverage End Date: 2019-06-04T23:59Z
## Message ID: 20190606-7D-001
##
## Disclaimer: NOAA's Space Weather Prediction Center (http://swpc.noaa.gov) is the United States Government official source for space weather forecasts. This "Experimental Research Information" consists of preliminary NASA research products and should be interpreted and used accordingly.


## Summary:

Solar activity was at low levels during this reporting period.  There were no significant flares or CMEs.  

Geomagnetic activity was at below minor levels with Kp index (a measure of geomagnetic activity, ranging 0-9) <=4 for the reporting period.

STEREO A IMPACT/PLASTIC instruments detected the arrival of a coronal hole high speed stream on 2019-06-01, with the solar wind speed at STEREO A reaching values of ~450 km/s on 2019-06-03.

The > 0.8 MeV energetic electron flux detected at GOES crossed the threshold level of 10^5 pfu starting at 2019-05-31T15:20Z and continued to be elevated until 2019-06-02 (see notifications 20190531-AL-001, 20190531-AL-002 and 20190602-AL-001). These significantly elevated energetic electron fluxes at geosynchronous orbit detected by GOES were associated with the coronal hole high speed stream detected by DSCOVR and ACE at L1 around 2019-05-28.

The energetic proton flux of >10 MeV protons detected at GOES and the 13-100 MeV protons at STEREO A were all at background levels for the entire reporting period. 

Space Weather Impact:
Space weather impacts on NASA spacecraft are expected to have been low to moderate this week due to the elevated energetic electron flux on the Earth's outer radiation belt described above.

## Outlook Coverage End Date:  2019-06-11T23:59Z

Solar activity is expected to be low for the upcoming week. Geomagnetic activity is expected to be low for the upcoming week, with some disturbance possible on or after 2019-06-08 due to the expected arrival of a minor coronal hole high speed stream.

## NASA Goddard Space Flight Center, Space Weather Research Center ( SWRC )
## Message Type: Space Weather Notification - Continued Radiation Belt Enhancement
##
## Message Issue Date: 2019-06-02T15:51:25Z
## Message ID: 20190602-AL-001
##
## Disclaimer: NOAA's Space Weather Prediction Center (http://swpc.noaa.gov) is the United States Government official source for space weather forecasts. This "Experimental Research Information" consists of preliminary NASA research products and should be interpreted and used accordingly.


## Summary:

This is an update to the notification with ID 20190531-AL-002. Energetic electron fluxes in the Earth's outer radiation belt continue to be significantly elevated. GOES "greater than 0.8 MeV" integral electron flux first exceeded 10^5 pfu starting at 2019-05-31T15:20Z and has continued to be above or near the threshold.

The elevated energetic electron flux levels are caused by the high speed stream starting at 2019-05-28T19:30Z.

NASA spacecraft at GEO, MEO and other orbits passing through or in the vicinity of the Earth's outer radiation belt can be impacted.

Activity ID: 2019-05-31T15:20:00-RBE-001.
